Threat(s) Not Associated With an Interaction:

1. Data Flow Owner Notification Is Potentially Interrupted  [State: Not Applicable]  [Priority: High] 

Category:Denial Of Service
Description:An external agent interrupts data flowing across a trust boundary in either direction.
Justification:Data crossing the boundary (notifications, encrypted vault retrieval) occurs over TLS-protected Bitwarden APIs. The protocol resists tampering but cannot prevent DoS; interruption results only in temporary unavailability, not unauthorized access.

2. External Entity Vault Owner Potentially Denies Receiving Data  [State: Mitigation Implemented]  [Priority: High] 

Category:Repudiation
Description:Vault Owner claims that it did not receive data from a process on the other side of the trust boundary. Consider using logging or auditing to record the source, time, and summary of the received data.
Justification:All emergency access notifications and approval events are recorded in an immutable audit log, including timestamp, sender, and event type, allowing reliable attribution if the owner claims they never received data.

3. Spoofing of the Vault Owner External Destination Entity  [State: Mitigation Implemented]  [Priority: High] 

Category:Spoofing
Description:Vault Owner may be spoofed by an attacker and this may lead to data being sent to the attacker's target instead of Vault Owner. Consider using a standard authentication mechanism to identify the external entity.
Justification:TLS and authenticated Bitwarden identity prevent spoofing of external entities.

4. Cross Site Request Forgery  [State: Not Applicable]  [Priority: High] 

Category:Elevation Of Privilege
Description:Cross-site request forgery (CSRF or XSRF) is a type of attack in which an attacker forces a user's browser to make a forged request to a vulnerable site by exploiting an existing trust relationship between the browser and the vulnerable web site. In a simple scenario, a user is logged in to web site A using a cookie as a credential. The other browses to web site B. Web site B returns a page with a hidden form that posts to web site A. Since the browser will carry the user's cookie to web site A, web site B now can take any action on web site A, for example, adding an admin to an account. The attack can be used to exploit any requests that the browser automatically authenticates, e.g. by session cookie, integrated authentication, IP whitelisting. The attack can be carried out in many ways such as by luring the victim to a site under control of the attacker, getting the user to click a link in a phishing email, or hacking a reputable web site that the victim will visit. The issue can only be resolved on the server side by requiring that all authenticated state-changing requests include an additional piece of secret payload (canary or CSRF token) which is known only to the legitimate web site and the browser and which is protected in transit through SSL/TLS. See the Forgery Protection property on the flow stencil for a list of mitigations.
Justification:The Bitwarden client is not a browser-based application and does not rely on cookies or implicit browser authentication, so CSRF is not applicable.

5. Elevation by Changing the Execution Flow in Waiting Period & Approval Handler  [State: Mitigation Implemented]  [Priority: High] 

Category:Elevation Of Privilege
Description:An attacker may pass data into Waiting Period & Approval Handler in order to change the flow of program execution within Waiting Period & Approval Handler to the attacker's choosing.
Justification:Only authenticated and validated approval metadata is accepted; malformed or unexpected input is rejected.

6. Waiting Period & Approval Handler May be Subject to Elevation of Privilege Using Remote Code Execution  [State: Mitigation Implemented]  [Priority: High] 

Category:Elevation Of Privilege
Description:Vault Owner may be able to remotely execute code for Waiting Period & Approval Handler.
Justification:Owner responses are simple metadata messages, not executable code; input parsing uses strict validation.

7. Elevation Using Impersonation  [State: Not Applicable]  [Priority: High] 

Category:Elevation Of Privilege
Description:Waiting Period & Approval Handler may be able to impersonate the context of Vault Owner in order to gain additional privilege.
Justification:Internal processes do not handle identity credentials and only process validated user-signed data.

8. Data Flow Approval Decision Is Potentially Interrupted  [State: Not Applicable]  [Priority: High] 

Category:Denial Of Service
Description:An external agent interrupts data flowing across a trust boundary in either direction.
Justification:TLS protects integrity but cannot prevent network interruption. Loss of connectivity only causes temporary unavailability, not unauthorized access.

9. Potential Process Crash or Stop for Waiting Period & Approval Handler  [State: Mitigation Implemented]  [Priority: High] 

Category:Denial Of Service
Description:Waiting Period & Approval Handler crashes, halts, stops or runs slowly; in all cases violating an availability metric.
Justification:Waiting period evaluation is lightweight and relies on OS runtime protections for fault tolerance.

10. Data Flow Sniffing  [State: Mitigation Implemented]  [Priority: High] 

Category:Information Disclosure
Description:Data flowing across Approval Decision may be sniffed by an attacker. Depending on what type of data an attacker can read, it may be used to attack other parts of the system or simply be a disclosure of information leading to compliance violations. Consider encrypting the data flow.
Justification:Approval messages are transmitted over TLS, preventing eavesdropping.

11. Potential Data Repudiation by Waiting Period & Approval Handler  [State: Mitigation Implemented]  [Priority: High] 

Category:Repudiation
Description:Waiting Period & Approval Handler claims that it did not receive data from a source outside the trust boundary. Consider using logging or auditing to record the source, time, and summary of the received data.
Justification:Audit logs record all access grants with timestamps, providing non-repudiation.

12. Potential Lack of Input Validation for Waiting Period & Approval Handler  [State: Mitigation Implemented]  [Priority: High] 

Category:Tampering
Description:Data flowing across Approval Decision may be tampered with by an attacker. This may lead to a denial of service attack against Waiting Period & Approval Handler or an elevation of privilege attack against Waiting Period & Approval Handler or an information disclosure by Waiting Period & Approval Handler. Failure to verify that input is as expected is a root cause of a very large number of exploitable issues. Consider all paths and the way they handle data. Verify that all input is verified for correctness using an approved list input validation approach.
Justification:Approval/denial responses travel over TLS and are validated by the Waiting Period Handler.

13. Potential Excessive Resource Consumption for Access Grant Generator or Audit Data Store  [State: Mitigation Implemented]  [Priority: High] 

Category:Denial Of Service
Description:Does Access Grant Generator or Audit Data Store take explicit steps to control resource consumption? Resource consumption attacks can be hard to deal with, and there are times that it makes sense to let the OS do the job. Be careful that your resource requests don't deadlock, and that they do timeout.
Justification:Both components perform simple operations and rely on OS-level protections for timeouts, memory, and I/O limits.

14. Spoofing of Destination Data Store Audit Data Store  [State: Not Applicable]  [Priority: High] 

Category:Spoofing
Description:Audit Data Store may be spoofed by an attacker and this may lead to data being written to the attacker's target instead of Audit Data Store. Consider using a standard authentication mechanism to identify the destination data store.
Justification:The Audit Store is an internal client-side component not externally addressable; destination cannot be changed at runtime.

15. Potential Excessive Resource Consumption for Waiting Period & Approval Handler or Audit Data Store  [State: Mitigation Implemented]  [Priority: High] 

Category:Denial Of Service
Description:Does Waiting Period & Approval Handler or Audit Data Store take explicit steps to control resource consumption? Resource consumption attacks can be hard to deal with, and there are times that it makes sense to let the OS do the job. Be careful that your resource requests don't deadlock, and that they do timeout.
Justification:These components perform lightweight state transitions and append-only log writes; OS-level scheduling, timeouts, and I/O limits prevent excessive memory or CPU usage during emergency access workflows.

16. Spoofing of Destination Data Store Audit Data Store  [State: Not Applicable]  [Priority: High] 

Category:Spoofing
Description:Audit Data Store may be spoofed by an attacker and this may lead to data being written to the attacker's target instead of Audit Data Store. Consider using a standard authentication mechanism to identify the destination data store.
Justification:<no mitigation provided>

17. Potential Excessive Resource Consumption for Access Request Validator or Audit Data Store  [State: Mitigation Implemented]  [Priority: High] 

Category:Denial Of Service
Description:Does Access Request Validator or Audit Data Store take explicit steps to control resource consumption? Resource consumption attacks can be hard to deal with, and there are times that it makes sense to let the OS do the job. Be careful that your resource requests don't deadlock, and that they do timeout.
Justification:The Access Request Validator handles simple metadata lookups and relies on the underlying OS and Bitwarden client runtime for rate limiting, timeouts, and memory management, which prevent local resource exhaustion.

18. Spoofing of Destination Data Store Audit Data Store  [State: Not Applicable]  [Priority: High] 

Category:Spoofing
Description:Audit Data Store may be spoofed by an attacker and this may lead to data being written to the attacker's target instead of Audit Data Store. Consider using a standard authentication mechanism to identify the destination data store.
Justification:Audit logs are written only to the local, trusted client store inside the Bitwarden Client Application Boundary. The process cannot dynamically choose a different destination, so an attacker cannot redirect writes to an external target.

19. Elevation Using Impersonation  [State: Not Applicable]  [Priority: High] 

Category:Elevation Of Privilege
Description:Access Grant Generator may be able to impersonate the context of Secrets Manager API in order to gain additional privilege.
Justification:The Access Grant Generator cannot impersonate the cloud API because encrypted vault data must come from the remote server, which requires authenticated network requests and cannot be faked by a local client process.

20. Spoofing the Secrets Manager API External Entity  [State: Mitigation Implemented]  [Priority: High] 

Category:Spoofing
Description:Secrets Manager API may be spoofed by an attacker and this may lead to unauthorized access to Access Grant Generator. Consider using a standard authentication mechanism to identify the external entity.
Justification:The client communicates with the real Secrets Manager API over TLS with certificate pinning, so a spoofed server cannot authenticate or present the valid Bitwarden certificate chain.

21. Elevation Using Impersonation  [State: Not Applicable]  [Priority: High] 

Category:Elevation Of Privilege
Description:Access Grant Generator may be able to impersonate the context of Waiting Period & Approval Handler in order to gain additional privilege.
Justification:The Access Grant Generator can only act after receiving a signed “Decision / Waiting Period Completed” message from the Waiting Period Handler, which is validated by the client workflow. It cannot self-trigger or fabricate approval metadata.

22. Spoofing the Vault Owner External Entity  [State: Mitigation Implemented]  [Priority: High] 

Category:Spoofing
Description:Vault Owner may be spoofed by an attacker and this may lead to unauthorized access to Waiting Period & Approval Handler. Consider using a standard authentication mechanism to identify the external entity.
Justification:Vault Owner identity is verified using Bitwarden login and MFA, preventing impersonation and unauthorized access.

23. Spoofing the Waiting Period & Approval Handler Process  [State: Mitigation Implemented]  [Priority: High] 

Category:Spoofing
Description:Waiting Period & Approval Handler may be spoofed by an attacker and this may lead to information disclosure by Vault Owner. Consider using a standard authentication mechanism to identify the destination process.
Justification:Vault Owner identity is verified using Bitwarden login and MFA, preventing impersonation and unauthorized access.

24. Elevation Using Impersonation  [State: Not Applicable]  [Priority: High] 

Category:Elevation Of Privilege
Description:Waiting Period & Approval Handler may be able to impersonate the context of Access Request Validator in order to gain additional privilege.
Justification:This process does not authenticate user identities; it only receives validated request metadata from the Access Request Validator. All emergency access workflows are driven by user-signed data, not by inter-process identity assumptions.

25. Weak Access Control for a Resource  [State: Mitigation Implemented]  [Priority: High] 

Category:Information Disclosure
Description:Improper data protection of Emergency Contact Config can allow an attacker to read information not intended for disclosure. Review authorization settings.
Justification:Emergency Contact Config is stored in the Bitwarden client as encrypted sync data, and only decrypted in-memory for authenticated users. Even if an attacker accesses the file, the data remains unreadable without the user’s master key.

26. Spoofing of Source Data Store Emergency Contact Config  [State: Mitigation Implemented]  [Priority: High] 

Category:Spoofing
Description:Emergency Contact Config may be spoofed by an attacker and this may lead to incorrect data delivered to Access Request Validator. Consider using a standard authentication mechanism to identify the source data store.
Justification:Emergency Contact Config is synchronized from Bitwarden’s cloud and validated cryptographically; the client cannot accept modified or spoofed configuration data because it is delivered only from authenticated API endpoints over TLS.

27. Elevation Using Impersonation  [State: Not Applicable]  [Priority: High] 

Category:Elevation Of Privilege
Description:Access Request Validator may be able to impersonate the context of Trusted Emergency Contact in order to gain additional privilege.
Justification:Internal processes cannot impersonate users because all emergency access requests must originate from an authenticated, signed-in Bitwarden account, and each request carries trusted-contact identifiers validated against server-side configuration.

28. Spoofing the Trusted Emergency Contact External Entity  [State: Mitigation Implemented]  [Priority: High] 

Category:Spoofing
Description:Trusted Emergency Contact may be spoofed by an attacker and this may lead to unauthorized access to Access Request Validator. Consider using a standard authentication mechanism to identify the external entity.
Justification:Bitwarden enforces strong authentication and verifies trusted-contact identity using Bitwarden account login + MFA + server-side contact validation. An attacker cannot gain access without matching a valid trusted-contact record stored in Emergency Contact Config.

29. Spoofing the Access Request Validator Process  [State: Mitigation Implemented]  [Priority: High] 

Category:Spoofing
Description:Access Request Validator may be spoofed by an attacker and this may lead to information disclosure by Trusted Emergency Contact. Consider using a standard authentication mechanism to identify the destination process.
Justification:Emergency Access Requests are transmitted over TLS to Bitwarden’s API, and the client validates all request metadata (trusted-contact ID, account ID, signatures). Tampered input is rejected before reaching core logic.

62. Collision Attacks  [State: Not Started]  [Priority: High] 

Category:Tampering
Description:Attackers who can send a series of packets or messages may be able to overlap data. For example, packet 1 may be 100 bytes starting at offset 0. Packet 2 may be 100 bytes starting at offset 25. Packet 2 will overwrite 75 bytes of packet 1. Ensure you reassemble data before filtering it, and ensure you explicitly handle these sorts of cases.
Justification:<no mitigation provided>

63. Replay Attacks  [State: Not Started]  [Priority: High] 

Category:Tampering
Description:Packets or messages without sequence numbers or timestamps can be captured and replayed in a wide variety of ways. Implement or utilize an existing communication protocol that supports anti-replay techniques (investigate sequence numbers before timers) and strong integrity.
Justification:<no mitigation provided>

153. Cross Site Request Forgery  [State: Not Started]  [Priority: High] 

Category:Elevation Of Privilege
Description:Cross-site request forgery (CSRF or XSRF) is a type of attack in which an attacker forces a user's browser to make a forged request to a vulnerable site by exploiting an existing trust relationship between the browser and the vulnerable web site. In a simple scenario, a user is logged in to web site A using a cookie as a credential. The other browses to web site B. Web site B returns a page with a hidden form that posts to web site A. Since the browser will carry the user's cookie to web site A, web site B now can take any action on web site A, for example, adding an admin to an account. The attack can be used to exploit any requests that the browser automatically authenticates, e.g. by session cookie, integrated authentication, IP whitelisting. The attack can be carried out in many ways such as by luring the victim to a site under control of the attacker, getting the user to click a link in a phishing email, or hacking a reputable web site that the victim will visit. The issue can only be resolved on the server side by requiring that all authenticated state-changing requests include an additional piece of secret payload (canary or CSRF token) which is known only to the legitimate web site and the browser and which is protected in transit through SSL/TLS. See the Forgery Protection property on the flow stencil for a list of mitigations.
Justification:<no mitigation provided>

Interaction: Vault UI Data
